<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-09T05:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-09T05:00:00-05:00" n="132" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d132">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">865.3311/57: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Fletcher</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-09T11:00:00+01:00"><hi rend="italic">April 9,
                                        1927—11 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 9—10:30
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>51. Your 29, April 8, 4 p.m. Press despatches put the cart before the
                            horse. The Fascist newspapers immediately attributed the accident to an
                            anti-Fascist plot; hence my alternative reference to possible sabotage,
                            promising thorough investigation. It was necessary and had a good
                            effect. Now, however, in the light of Pinedo’s statement which has been
                            published here it is generally understood that there was no anti-Fascist
                            connection.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Fletcher</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
